    title: "Praise the Work, Not the Child",
    summary: "Praising effort and strategy builds resilience; praising intelligence actually undermines it.",
    body: "Research by Mueller and Dweck (1998) tested different types of praise on children aged 10-11 — the exact age group preparing for the 11+. The results were striking. Children praised for intelligence ('You must be really smart!') subsequently chose easier tasks, showed less persistence after failure, and performed worse. Children praised for effort ('You must have worked really hard!') chose harder challenges, persisted longer, and actually improved their performance after setbacks.\n\nThe mechanism is straightforward: when you tell a child they are clever, they hear that their worth comes from a fixed trait. When they then struggle, they conclude they must not be clever after all. But when you praise what they did — their effort, their strategy, their persistence — they learn that these things are within their control.\n\nHere are direct phrase swaps to practise:\n\nInstead of 'You're so clever!' try 'You worked really hard on that.'\nInstead of 'You're a natural at maths!' try 'Your method for solving that was really good.'\nInstead of 'That was easy for you!' try 'I noticed you tried three different approaches before you got it — that's great problem-solving.'\nInstead of 'You got 100%!' try 'You can see the difference all that practice has made.'\n\nThis is not about withholding praise — it is about directing it at the right thing. A follow-up study by Gunderson et al. (2013) found that parents' process praise to young children predicted their growth mindset five years later.",
    researchNote: "Mueller & Dweck (1998), Journal of Personality and Social Psychology; Gunderson et al. (2013), Child Development",
    contextTrigger: null
