    category: 'How to Praise & Respond',
    title: "Why 'Try Harder' Does Not Work (And What to Say Instead)",
    summary: "Telling a struggling child to try harder implies the problem is effort — when it is almost always strategy.",
    body: "Carol Dweck flagged this in her own 2015 correction of how growth mindset was being misapplied: 'A growth mindset isn't just about effort. If a child is working hard but their strategy isn't working, telling them to keep trying is not helpful — they need to try something different.'\n\nThis matters because 'try harder' carries a hidden accusation: you were not trying hard enough. For a child who is already struggling, this is both untrue and demoralising. It also provides no useful information — harder how? At what? In which way?\n\nSaying 'you can do it if you try harder' to a child who lacks the necessary skills or strategies is not encouragement. Dweck called this 'using growth mindset as consolation rather than empowerment.' It will ultimately undermine the child's trust in you because they will try harder, still fail, and conclude that the real problem is them.\n\nHere is what to say instead:\n\n'What strategy did you use? Let's see if there's a different approach.' This shifts the focus from raw effort to method.\n\n'Let's go back a step — which part makes sense, and where does it stop making sense?' This helps locate the actual gap in understanding.\n\n'You've been working hard on this and it's still tricky. That tells me we need a new approach, not more of the same.' This validates their effort, removes the blame, and pivots to something practical.\n\nThe research is clear: praise effort that is producing learning, but when effort alone is not working, the child needs a new strategy, not a louder instruction to keep going.",
