    summary: "Noticing and praising strategy changes builds the flexible thinking the 11+ demands.",
    body: "The GL Assessment 11+ is designed to test whether children can apply knowledge flexibly across unfamiliar problem formats. This means the ability to switch strategies when one approach is not working is arguably more important than getting any single answer correct.\n\nResearch supports this directly. Dweck's work found that children praised for process maintained or increased their engagement even after difficult problems. But Dweck (2015) made an important clarification: process praise must be tied to outcomes, not offered as empty comfort. 'Great effort!' disconnected from any learning is just as unhelpful as 'You're so clever!'\n\nEffective strategy praise sounds like this:\n\n'You tried long division a different way this time — that's exactly what good mathematicians do.' This names the specific strategy change.\n\n'When you checked your work, you caught that mistake — that's a really useful habit.' This links a process to a concrete positive outcome.\n\n'You tried three different approaches before you found one that worked. That persistence paid off.' This connects effort and strategy to the result.\n\n'You used estimation first to check whether your answer was sensible — that was a smart move.' This highlights a metacognitive skill.\n\nContrast these with praise that does not work: 'Well done!' (too vague). 'You're so clever!' (praises a trait, not a choice). 'Great effort!' (disconnected from outcome).\n\nThe EEF rates metacognition — thinking about your own thinking and choosing appropriate strategies — as having an average impact of +8 months of additional progress. When you notice and name strategy changes, you are building this metacognitive awareness directly.",
