    summary: "Parental anxiety about the exam is contagious — the research shows it transmits directly to children through parenting style.",
    body: "Research published in Frontiers in Psychology (2024) demonstrated that parents' education anxiety directly influences children's learning anxiety, transmitted through parenting style. Rejection and overprotection made this worse. Emotional warmth was the strongest protective factor.\n\nSelf-Determination Theory (Deci and Ryan, 2000) identifies three psychological needs that drive motivation: autonomy (feeling ownership), competence (feeling capable), and relatedness (feeling connected). Pressure undermines all three. It removes autonomy ('you must study'), threatens competence ('you're not doing well enough'), and damages relatedness (the parent becomes a taskmaster rather than a supporter).\n\nHere is how encouragement and pressure differ in practice:\n\nEncouragement sounds like: 'Would you like to do maths or English first today?' Pressure sounds like: 'You need to do an hour of maths before any screen time.'\n\nEncouragement: 'You've improved so much on fractions — your practice is really paying off.' Pressure: 'You still need to get better at fractions before the exam.'\n\nEncouragement: 'How do you feel about that session? What was the hardest part?' Pressure: 'What did you get? Show me your score.'\n\nEncouragement: 'Let's take a break today — you've been working really hard this week.' Pressure: 'We can't afford to miss a day — the exam is getting closer.'\n\nPractical test: if the exam is the first topic of conversation when your child gets home from school, it has crossed from encouragement into pressure.",
