    summary: "The conversation after practice matters as much as the practice itself — focus on process, learning, and what comes next.",
    body: "Every practice session ends with a conversation, even if it is just a few words. Research shows this moment shapes whether your child approaches the next session with motivation or dread.\n\nAfter a good session, resist the temptation to praise the score. Mueller and Dweck's research showed that children praised for outcomes became less willing to take on challenges. Instead, praise what they did:\n\n'I noticed you slowed down on the tricky questions instead of rushing — that's a really mature approach.'\n'You finished that session really focused. How did that feel?'\n'What was the most interesting thing you learned today?'\n\nAfter a difficult session, your job is to protect motivation for next time. Bandura's self-efficacy research shows that mastery experiences are the most powerful confidence builder, so help the child find genuine progress even in a hard session:\n\n'Which questions did you feel good about? Let's start there.'\n'That was a tough set. What's one thing you understand now that you didn't before?'\n'Some of those questions were above your level — that's why they felt hard. We'll build up to those.'\n\nAfter any session, the three most useful questions are:\n\n1. 'What went well?' — trains the child to notice their own strengths.\n2. 'What was tricky?' — builds metacognitive awareness (rated +8 months by the EEF).\n3. 'What do you want to work on next time?' — gives them autonomy, which Self-Determination Theory identifies as essential for sustained motivation.\n\nAvoid asking 'What did you get?' as your opening question. This signals that the score is what matters most to you.",
