    category: 'Understanding How Practice Works',
    title: "The 80% Sweet Spot — Why Too Easy and Too Hard Are Both Problems",
    summary: "Research shows children learn best when they get roughly 80% of practice questions right.",
    body: "Educational researcher Barak Rosenshine studied decades of classroom data to find what the most effective teachers had in common. One of his clearest findings: during guided practice, students should be getting approximately 80% of questions correct.\n\nThis number is not arbitrary. It sits in what psychologists call the Zone of Proximal Development — the gap between what a child can already do independently and what is just beyond their reach. At 80% success, your child is being stretched by the 20% they get wrong, but building genuine confidence from the 80% they get right.\n\nWhen success rates are much higher than 80%, the practice is too easy. It might feel productive — your child breezes through, scores look great — but very little learning is happening. The brain is not being challenged enough to build new connections.\n\nWhen success rates drop well below 80%, the practice is too hard. Repeated failure does not toughen children up — it destroys their belief that they can improve. Research on self-efficacy is clear: repeated failure experiences are the fastest way to destroy self-efficacy. A child grinding through questions they cannot answer is not learning resilience; they are learning helplessness.\n\nIf your child is consistently scoring above 90% on a topic, it is time to move to harder questions or a new topic. If they are consistently below 60%, step back to build the foundations first.",
