    summary: "Research shows that parental education anxiety directly transmits to children through everyday behaviour and parenting style.",
    body: "This may be uncomfortable to read, but the research is clear: your anxiety about the 11+ is contagious. A 2024 study published in Frontiers in Psychology found that parents' education anxiety directly influences children's learning anxiety — and the mechanism is parenting style. Rejection and overprotection make the transmission worse. Emotional warmth reduces it.\n\nYou do not need to be visibly panicking for your child to absorb your stress. Checking their scores obsessively, making the exam the dominant topic of conversation, comparing their progress with other children, or tensing up when they get questions wrong — all of these transmit anxiety, even when your words say 'don't worry.'\n\nChildren are remarkably sensitive to emotional undercurrents. They read your face before they read the question. Research found that 70% of students experience some form of learning anxiety, and parental pressure is a significant contributor to academic burnout.\n\nWhat actually helps is genuine calm — not performed calm. That means doing your own anxiety work first. Talk to other parents. Acknowledge your fears privately. Remind yourself of the evidence: grammar school attendance provides only a modest advantage, and the 11+ does not determine your child's future.\n\nThe single strongest protective factor the research identifies is emotional warmth combined with calm confidence. Your child needs to feel that you believe in them — and that you will be fine whatever happens.",
