    title: "Box Breathing and Grounding — Practical Techniques to Practise at Home",
    summary: "Evidence-based breathing and grounding techniques can reduce anxiety significantly with regular practice, and can be used silently during the exam.",
    body: "These two techniques are drawn from clinical psychology and have strong evidence bases. The key is to practise them regularly at home so they become automatic — not something your child has to remember under pressure.\n\nBox Breathing works because the extended exhalation stimulates the vagus nerve, activating the parasympathetic nervous system — your body's built-in calming response.\n\nTeach it like this: Breathe in for 4 counts ('smell a flower'), hold for 4 counts ('you are underwater'), breathe out for 4 counts ('blow out candles'), hold empty for 4 counts ('wait for the next wave'). Repeat three or four times. For older children comfortable with the pattern, try 4-7-8 breathing — in for 4, hold for 7, out for 8. The longer exhale is what triggers the calming response.\n\nThe 5-4-3-2-1 Grounding Technique comes from cognitive-behavioural therapy. It interrupts the anxiety spiral by redirecting attention to the present moment. Find 5 things you can see, 4 things you can touch, 3 you can hear, 2 you can smell, 1 you can taste. A randomised trial of 121 children with anxiety found grounding exercises led to a significant reduction in anxiety scores.\n\nBoth techniques can be done silently in under 60 seconds — practical even during an exam. But they only work if they are practised. Make box breathing part of your bedtime routine. Start now, not the week before the exam.",
