    id: 'parent-anxiety-not-how-clever',
    category: 'Managing Anxiety',
    title: "Never Frame the 11+ as Measuring 'How Clever' Your Child Is",
    summary: "Framing the exam as a test of intelligence activates stereotype threat and fixed mindset, both of which measurably reduce performance.",
    body: "The language you use about the 11+ matters more than you might think. Research on stereotype threat found that children underperform when they believe a test is measuring their intelligence. This effect is stronger in primary school children than in older students.\n\nHere is why it happens. When a child believes the exam measures 'how clever' they are, two damaging processes activate. First, stereotype threat: the child becomes hyperaware of the possibility of confirming that they are 'not clever enough,' which consumes working memory and degrades performance. Second, fixed mindset: Mueller and Dweck's landmark 1998 study found that children praised for intelligence chose easier tasks, showed less persistence after failure, and performed worse than children praised for effort.\n\nThe practical difference is stark. Children who believe intelligence is fixed think mistakes prove they are not smart. Children who believe ability grows through effort treat mistakes as information.\n\nWhat to say instead: 'The 11+ tests what you have learned and how well you can show your skills.' Talk about preparation and practice, not natural ability. When your child does well, say 'You can see the difference all that practice has made' rather than 'You are so clever.' When they struggle, say 'What could you try differently?' rather than 'You are really good at this — just try harder.'\n\nThis matters for girls especially. Research showed that maths anxiety in authority figures transmitted specifically to girls, lowering their scores. Provide female role models in maths and science, and frame the exam as a skills demonstration, never an intelligence test.",
    researchNote: "Mueller & Dweck (1998); Stereotype threat meta-analysis, European Journal of Psychology of Education (2025); Beilock on teacher anxiety transmission",
