    title: "Sleep Is the Foundation of Learning",
    summary: "Children aged 9-11 need 9-12 hours of sleep because memory consolidation happens during sleep, not during study.",
    body: "Sleep is not downtime for the brain. It is when the real work of learning happens. During sleep, your child's brain replays and reorganises everything they studied that day, strengthening neural connections and integrating new knowledge with what they already know. Cut sleep short and you cut this process short.\n\nThe research is unambiguous. Sadeh et al. (2003) studied children aged 9-12 and found that extending sleep by just one hour measurably improved cognitive performance, while restricting sleep by one hour measurably worsened it. That is a two-hour swing from a single hour's difference. Wilhelm et al. (2020) found that children actually consolidate memories during sleep more efficiently than adults. Backhaus et al. (2008) showed children improved by 25% on problem-solving tasks after sleep, with no improvement after the same period awake.\n\nThe recommended amount is 9-12 hours per night for children aged 6-12, with 10-11 hours being optimal for 9-11 year olds. An NIH study of 8,000 children found that those sleeping fewer than 9 hours had reduced grey matter volume in brain areas governing attention, memory, and impulse control.\n\nIf your child must miss a study session, it is better to skip it entirely than to push it late into the evening at the cost of sleep. A well-rested brain with 90% of the knowledge will outperform a tired brain with 95% every single time. Set a consistent bedtime and wake time, including weekends, and treat it as non-negotiable.",
    researchNote: "Sadeh et al. (2003); Wilhelm et al. (2020), Nature Scientific Reports; Backhaus et al. (2008), Journal of Sleep Research",
