    summary: "Physical exercise improves the exact cognitive skills the 11+ tests, so cancelling it for more revision is counterproductive.",
    body: "It is tempting to think that dropping football practice or swimming lessons frees up valuable revision time. The research says the opposite. Physical activity directly improves the cognitive skills your child needs for the 11+ exam, and removing it makes them worse at exactly the things the test measures.\n\nHillman et al. (2009) found that after aerobic exercise, children's performance improved specifically on tasks involving executive function: planning, working memory, and inhibitory control. These are the higher-order skills that underpin every section of the GL Assessment. A meta-analysis by Alvarez-Bueno et al. (2017) confirmed that the strongest cognitive benefits of physical activity in children are to executive function.\n\nThe benefits are not just long-term. A single 20-minute bout of moderate exercise improves concentration, reading, and maths performance for the period that follows. The NHS recommends at least 60 minutes of physical activity daily for children.\n\nSports involving cognitive demands, such as football, basketball, or tennis, enhance executive function more than simple aerobic exercise, because they require split-second decision-making, spatial awareness, and rule-following under pressure. Team sports also provide social connection, which reduces stress and supports motivation.\n\nThe systematic review by Donnelly et al. (2016) found no evidence that increased physical activity negatively affects academic achievement. None. Exercise before a study session is one of the most effective things your child can do. Protect their sport and play time fiercely.",
