    summary: "Screens before bed suppress melatonin and disrupt the sleep that consolidates your child's learning.",
    body: "Blue light from screens suppresses melatonin, the hormone that signals the brain it is time to sleep. This is not a marginal effect. It delays sleep onset, reduces sleep quality, and directly undermines the memory consolidation process that makes studying worthwhile in the first place.\n\nResearch published in MDPI (2024) found that excessive screen time is associated with poorer sleep, reduced physical activity, attention difficulties, and challenges in emotional and social functioning. A 2025 study linked greater screen exposure to reduced white matter integrity in brain regions supporting language and literacy.\n\nThe rule is straightforward: all screens off at least one hour before bed. This includes phones, tablets, televisions, and gaming devices. The 11+ prep app counts as educational screen time, but it still emits blue light, so finish any app-based practice well before the wind-down period.\n\nEnforcing this without nightly battles requires making it a household rule rather than a punishment. Everyone follows it, including parents. Replace screen time with calm activities: reading a physical book, drawing, board games, or gentle conversation. Establish the routine early so it feels normal by exam time, not like something imposed under pressure.\n\nKeep devices out of the bedroom entirely. The bed should be associated with sleep, not stimulation. No exam discussion at bedtime either. The evening is for winding down, not ramping up anxiety about tomorrow's practice session.",
