    title: "Recognising Burnout: Six Warning Signs",
    summary: "Academic burnout is a measurable condition with clear warning signs that parents can spot early if they know what to look for.",
    body: "Academic burnout in children is not just being tired. Research defines it as a measurable psychological condition with three components: emotional exhaustion, cynicism towards schoolwork, and a reduced sense of accomplishment. Burnout is associated with depressive symptoms, diminished life satisfaction, disrupted sleep, physical complaints, and academic disengagement. Pushing through burnout does not build resilience. It makes everything worse.\n\nHere are the six warning signs to watch for:\n\n1. Physical complaints. Frequent stomachaches or headaches, particularly before study time or school. These are not made up. Stress produces real physical symptoms in children.\n\n2. Emotional changes. Increased irritability, mood swings, tearfulness, or a flattened emotional response where your child seems checked out.\n\n3. Behavioural withdrawal. Loss of interest in hobbies, friends, or activities they previously enjoyed. The world is shrinking to just schoolwork and pressure.\n\n4. Avoidance. Procrastination, excuses, hiding books, or conveniently forgetting practice sessions. This is not laziness. It is a child's way of protecting themselves from something that has become overwhelming.\n\n5. Sleep disruption. Difficulty falling asleep, nightmares about exams, or sleeping excessively as a form of escape.\n\n6. Regression. Behaving younger than their age, increased clinginess, or needing significantly more reassurance than usual.\n\nIf you spot these signs, reduce the study load immediately. This is not optional. Prioritise play, rest, and social connection. If symptoms persist beyond two to three weeks, seek professional support. No exam result is worth your child's mental health.",
