    summary: "In the final days before the exam, protect sleep, maintain exercise, do only light revision, and guard your child's downtime.",
    body: "The week before the exam is not the time for heroic cramming. Over 140 years of cognitive science research consistently demonstrates that cramming is one of the least effective ways to learn. It disrupts sleep, which disrupts memory consolidation, which means your child literally cannot retain what they are trying to force in.\n\nHere is what the final week should look like:\n\nSleep comes first. Maintain the same bedtime and wake time your child has had throughout preparation. Aim for 10-11 hours. The night before the exam, prioritise sleep above everything.\n\nKeep exercise in the routine. A 20-minute walk or active play on the morning of the exam boosts concentration and calms the nervous system. During the final week, maintain normal sport and activity schedules.\n\nRevision should be light. Brief reviews of familiar material only. No new topics. No difficult questions designed to stretch. The purpose is to maintain confidence and keep knowledge accessible, not to learn anything new.\n\nProtect downtime fiercely. Your child needs normal life in the days before the exam: seeing friends, playing outside, reading for fun, being bored. Filling every moment with revision communicates that you do not believe they are ready, which undermines the confidence they need on the day.\n\nOn exam morning: arrive early, because rushing creates physiological stress that takes 15-20 minutes to subside. A calm, well-rested, physically active child walking into that exam room is in the best possible position to show what they know.",
